 testing strategies**\\n\\nI’m considering the use of JUnit nested tests with one top-level file. I can't fork per method unless Gradle maxParallel is adjusted, which feels tricky. But I wonder if dynamic-access coverage could aggregate in a child process if the agent is inherited via JAVA_TOOL_OPTIONS. Typically, agent options are passed to the test JVM, not the child. So, I can’t rely on that. Maybe using `SnappyLoader` through a public API is a potential option?\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_qiHbOiTMn5xS0bciWUqqkntf|fc_0b01435cdb5be1c0016a3d6a659db88193be035589333ca1a6", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "/home/mihailo/git/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/local_repositories/source_context/org.xerial.snappy/snappy-java/1.0.4.1/main/extracted/org/xerial/snappy/SnappyInputStream.java", "limit": 120}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 10446, "output": 2082, "cacheRead": 16896, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 29424, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1782409781609, "responseId": "resp_0b01435cdb5be1c0016a3d6a36698c8193975eb6e0988f033e"}}
