[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating Gradle test rules**\n\nI’m thinking about Gradle tests and how the `forkEvery` option relates to max test classes. I wonder if having the same class with two methods would cause issues when using the same JVM. The rule is about keeping dynamic-access classes in their own dedicated Java test files, which seems to suggest a one-to-one mapping. Okay, so does that mean multiple top-level classes can be in the same file? It looks like only one public top-level class is allowed, so all top-level test classes must be public.\n\n**Considering Gradle and Test Tasks**\n\nI'm contemplating if I could introduce two Test tasks in Gradle. It seems like the dynamic access report might only come from the default test, and I'm not sure if TCK only runs the test task. I need to look into whether \"forkEvery\" can be configured for test tasks. It feels tricky since it may relate to how JUnit organizes tests in classes. We really want to ensure we're covering supported behavior without asserting known failures, right?\n\n**Exploring Snappy Error Handling**\n\nI'm thinking about how to cover scenarios where known failures shouldn't be asserted. If we consider the native image and coverage requirements, I wonder if I could catch a SnappyError when the system library is missing. It gets tricky, though, because the Static implementation might be null while the class initializes. If I adjust the settings to disable bundled libraries and use a real system library, I might navigate around the package-private access issue. I need to ensure all necessary paths are covered effectively!\n\n**Considering SnappyLoader Implementation**\n\nI’m wondering if setting \"useSystemLib=false\" after the system library branch could help, allowing SnappyLoader.load to recognize the API already in place, which would skip line 383. It feels complicated since bundling first and then switching t